What are geo-data?

Types of geodata

[1] absolute geo-data

  • GPS data ð
  • projection via a coordinate reference system (CRS) ðºï¸

[2] relative geo-data

  • âat homeâ ð 
  • dominating the human use of geo-data ð¬
  • \(\rightarrow\) need to be connected to other types of geo-data

Structured and unstructured geo-data

  • structured: organization of the data facilitates processing by computer (e.g.Â shapefile format of vector data) ð¨âð»ï¸

  • unstructured: geo-information must first be extracted using methods such as geocoding, geotagging or geoparsing ðµï¸

  • Example
  • Output
  • âSimple Featuresâ objects are data.frames
  • additional dimension to each observation: certain type of geoinformation (geometry column), e.g.Â 
    • points (described by one pair of coordinates) ðµ
    • Lines (described by two coordinate pairs) â
    • Polygons (described by at least three coordinate pairs)
    • âRegular Gridâ (described by a pair of coordinates for the center of gravity + grid size)
# Create a sub-directory
directory_name <- "./data"

        "Directory exists",

Visualisation of spatial data

  • Overview
  • Example
  • Output
  • ânormalâ dataframe
  • additional column: geometry
  • spatial data can be easily visualized with ggplot
  • the corresponding ggplot layer is called geom_sf
  • âï¸ using geographical information, we can link a variety of different (unrelated) data sources
ggplot(data = electoral_districts_shp) +
    geom_sf() +
    theme_bw()

Linking spatial data to other data sources

  • Overview
  • Example
  • Output
  • any data that shares an identifier with the sf data can be linked
  • identifiers can carry implicit spatial dimension, e.g.:
    • country name
    • state names
    • electoral districts
  • BUT: just because data can be mapped does not always mean it should be mapped?
  • How to avoid being fooled by maps
electoral_data_url <- "https://www.bundeswahlleiter.de/dam/jcr/2a90d988-7063-48af-b265-dfb9fa14f7e3/btw21_kerg2.csv"
electoral_data <- read_csv2(electoral_data_url,
                            skip = 9) %>%
  filter(Gebietsart == "Wahlkreis") %>%
  filter(Stimme == 2) %>%
  filter(Gruppenname == "AfD") %>%
  rename(electoral_district_id = Gebietsnummer,
         party = Gruppenname,
         afd_vote_share = Prozent) %>%
  select(electoral_district_id,
         party,
         afd_vote_share)

head(electoral_data)

# generate character id to match the data to the shape file
electoral_districts_shp <- electoral_districts_shp %>%
  mutate(electoral_district_id = str_pad(
    as.character(WKR_NR),
    pad = "0",
    width = 3,
    side = "left"
  ))
# left_join (!) to shape file
electoral_districts_shp <- electoral_districts_shp %>%
    left_join(.,
        electoral_data,
       by = c("electoral_district_id")
       )


# plot the vote share of AfD
afd_vote_plot <- ggplot(data = electoral_districts_shp) +
  geom_sf(aes(fill = afd_vote_share)) +
  theme_void() + 
  scale_fill_distiller(trans = "reverse", 
                       name = "AfD Vote Share")
afd_vote_plot

Contrasting different spatial distributions

  • Overview
  • Example
  • Output
  • use patchwork to show two spatial distributions side-by-side
# add the official socio-demographic information for the electoral districts
structural_data_url <- "https://www.bundeswahlleiter.de/dam/jcr/b1d3fc4f-17eb-455f-a01c-a0bf32135c5d/btw21_strukturdaten.csv" # nolint
structural_data <- read_csv2(structural_data_url,
                           skip = 8) %>%
  rename(electoral_district_id = `Wahlkreis-Nr.`,
         electoral_district_name = `Wahlkreis-Name`,
         foreigner_share = `BevÃ¶lkerung am 31.12.2019 - AuslÃ¤nder/-innen (%)`) %>% 
  select(electoral_district_id,
         electoral_district_name,
         foreigner_share) %>%
  # keep only observations that relate to electoral districts
  filter(!str_detect(electoral_district_name,
                     pattern = "[Ii]nsgesamt"))


# add the share of foreigners to the shape file 
electoral_districts_shp <- electoral_districts_shp %>%
  left_join(.,
            structural_data,
            by = c("electoral_district_id")
  )

# plot the share of foreigners
foreigner_share_plot <- ggplot(data = electoral_districts_shp) +
  geom_sf(aes(fill = foreigner_share)) +
  theme_void() + 
  scale_fill_distiller(direction = 1, 
                       palette = "BuGn",
                       name = "Share of Foreigners"
                       )
foreigner_share_plot


# show both plots side-by-side
afd_vote_plot + foreigner_share_plot +
    plot_layout(guides = 'collect')
